Remarkable architecture located between Quai de la Râpée and Gare d'Austerlitz, the viaduct was created with the aim of passing the metro. The elegant arched line of this viaduct is astonishing with the other stone bridges. The bold metal structure created by the brilliant architect Formigé and the ornamentalist Kulikowski, is a nice nod to the mastery of casting and work of Effeil's works. Built in approximately 9 months, a technical feat, with a span of 107.20m, it is a marvel of lightness.

The Austerlitz Viaduct is a railway bridge that crosses the Seine in Paris (France), built by the Société de Construction de Levallois-Perret;  It is used by trains on line 5 of the Paris metro.  It is listed as a historical monument by decree of June 12, 19861.

A superb work of railway art created by the no less famous Eiffel company. This arc-shaped steel bridge is impressive by its span of 140 meters above the Seine and by the decorative motifs featuring the coat of arms of Paris placed on Poseidon's trident. One of the most beautiful bridges in Paris as far as I am concerned, you have to go down to the quay of the same name to appreciate every detail of its decorations worthy of artistic ironwork.

Surprising bridge: coming from Place d'Italie you leave Austerlitz station high up to cross the quay then the Seine before taking a sharp turn to the left, a bit like a rollercoaster. To do once in a metro and pretty to see from the outside.

Austerlitz Viaduct A railway bridge built in 1903-1904 over the Seine River on Metro Line 5. The design was by Jean Camus Formique. The Austerlitz Viaduct can be seen in the distance, and the road bridge that is being crossed in the photo is the Austerlitz Bridge, which is one of the historical heritage sites.

THE AUSTERLITZ VIADUCT IS A RAILWAY BRIDGE CREATED BY THE EIFFEL COMPANY BETWEEN 1903 1904.

Very beautiful work which evokes a type of construction similar to the Eiffel Tower and the Debilly footbridge as well!! It was also produced by the Eiffel company; it is used by the trains of line 5 of the Paris metro and is listed as a historic monument by decree of June 12, 1986. The decoration of the Austerlitz viaduct was entrusted to Jean Camille Formigé, also responsible for the architecture of the superstructures of the Paris metro. He composed it with various marine symbols (fish, oars, anchors, tridents). The arms of Paris are also present at the bottom of the arches. Construction took place between 1903 and 1904. The structure then had the longest span of the Parisian bridges with 140 m, ahead of the Alexandre-III bridge built three years earlier (since surpassed only by the Charles-de-Gaulle bridge). Close to the metro station: Gare d'Austerlitz...

The bridge over the Seine allows you to quickly travel from the Gare d'Austerlitz to the Gare de Lyon in Paris. There is a beautiful view from the bridge.

The helical viaduct allows the crossing of the Seine by metro line 5, it is located between the Gare d'Austerlitz and Quai de la Rapée stations. The viaduct was put into service on July 13, 1906 during the extension of line 5 from Gare d'Austerlitz to Place Mazas (currently Quai de la Rapée) note that during the first 2 weeks the line went as far as Gare de Lyon by a turnaround of the trains at Mazas but given the mess for the operation this section was removed.
